1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:28,248
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

2
00:00:30,219 --> 00:00:34,165
So we're going through the first discourse.

3
00:00:34,286 --> 00:00:37,051
It's known as the first discourse that the Buddha gave.

4
00:00:38,512 --> 00:00:41,137
It obviously wasn't done in this way.

5
00:00:41,176 --> 00:00:45,362
He was probably just in conversation with the five companions.

6
00:00:45,844 --> 00:00:52,033
But later on it got systemized into this, formalized into this discourse.

7
00:00:52,515 --> 00:00:57,341
And it's the basic platform of all the Buddha's teachings, the Four Noble Truths, Eightfold Path.

8
00:00:59,177 --> 00:01:05,846
And last week we just introduced it and we talked really about the whole problems of this sensual pleasure business.

9
00:01:05,885 --> 00:01:12,073
Remember he says, monks, these two extremes should not be followed by one who's gone forth into homelessness.

10
00:01:12,213 --> 00:01:16,459
Remember what we mean by that is somebody who's gone into the spiritual life.

11
00:01:16,480 --> 00:01:16,939
What to?

12
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:27,112
The pursuit of happiness, sensual happiness in sensual pleasures, which is low, vulgar, the way of worldlings, ignoble and unbeneficial.

13
00:01:27,132 --> 00:01:28,915
So he hasn't got a good word for it.

14
00:01:30,295 --> 00:01:59,930
for indulgence of any sort see especially around Christmas and then there's now the second one is the pursuit of self-mortification see which is painful ignoble and unbeneficial now in those days there were those teachers who taught these blissful states what we now call the jhanas which the Buddha felt were very worthwhile because they develop beautiful mental states

15
00:02:00,231 --> 00:02:29,580
the one about for instance Metta if you keep developing that then your whole mind is suffused your whole heart is suffused with this good will so you didn't see any problem with that apart from the usual attachment that one gets with beautiful states of mind it's like when you walk in the country you get attached to it and you want to go out there again but the other thing was this self-mortification and the understanding even which predates the Buddha was this whole business of desire this wasn't something

16
00:02:29,897 --> 00:02:58,368
specific to the Buddha the fact that desire was the cause of suffering it was there in some understanding or other even Socrates said it Socrates said desire is the cause of suffering so the whole idea was that this sensual pleasure which was the world right the world somehow if you want to be liberated from the world one other way to do it would be to reduce the appetites of the body so one obvious way is to fast

17
00:02:59,125 --> 00:03:00,347
So this is what the Buddha did.

18
00:03:00,366 --> 00:03:02,490
One of his main exercises was to fast.

19
00:03:02,509 --> 00:03:04,854
In fact, it seems to be the main one that he did.

20
00:03:05,433 --> 00:03:08,378
He said he got so thin he could hold his spine through his stomach.

21
00:03:09,700 --> 00:03:11,323
He tried that.

22
00:03:11,342 --> 00:03:27,106
And the whole idea was that by reducing the appetites of the body, you necessarily reduced your desire for them.

23
00:03:27,745 --> 00:03:30,788
Now, have you ever done a fast, a 10-day fast?

24
00:03:30,808 --> 00:03:35,074
Well, what happens is the first three days are pretty awful as the body detoxes itself.

25
00:03:35,133 --> 00:03:39,479
But then suddenly, you get into a very nice place and you don't feel hungry.

26
00:03:40,540 --> 00:03:42,342
And the reason is the body starts eating itself.

27
00:03:42,963 --> 00:03:43,844
You're actually dying.

28
00:03:45,347 --> 00:03:46,669
But you never feel hungry.

29
00:03:46,769 --> 00:03:47,610
You feel very light.

30
00:03:48,229 --> 00:03:50,774
Very light, you know, it's fantastic really.

31
00:03:51,033 --> 00:03:53,516
And you can understand why people make a habit of it.

32
00:03:54,052 --> 00:04:00,198
and why it became such a thing in yoga to do long fasts, you know, because it is very purifying.

33
00:04:00,217 --> 00:04:03,501
And your appetite is simply reduced.

34
00:04:03,901 --> 00:04:05,622
Somehow it's just not there.

35
00:04:05,643 --> 00:04:08,906
You just don't feel hungry after a while, and the body feels very light.

36
00:04:11,867 --> 00:04:19,214
Other mortification exercises were to sit next to a fire and sort of make, and suffer the heat.

37
00:04:19,334 --> 00:04:23,098
It was, you know, other words, you'll see them even today in yoga,

38
00:04:23,752 --> 00:04:52,343
in India you know with their arms withered still held up in the air never pulled down and it's all to do with trying to get rid of the body almost it's seeing the body as something which is hateful to be despised to be got rid of to be conquered to be you know there's some negative feeling towards the body and of course we get it through Christianity as well and especially through its

39
00:04:52,862 --> 00:05:18,245
judgments around sexual activity there's something impure about it so this was the practice of the time and again it was all to do with rebirth it was all to do with liberating the atta the self from the body this is the way you did it you stopped it from seeking happiness in the body and one way to do it of course is to make the body painful

40
00:05:19,762 --> 00:05:27,930
But I think we can stretch this a bit more, like last time I was talking about the psychological consequences of indulgence.

41
00:05:28,571 --> 00:05:31,754
The boredom, you know, the grief at loss, etc., etc.

42
00:05:32,516 --> 00:05:41,625
Here, what we find is all the stuff that Freud really understood about repression and about self-hatred and about self-judgment.

43
00:05:42,225 --> 00:05:46,711
Because to me, all that comes into that negative part, which actually is making us suffer.

44
00:05:47,591 --> 00:05:48,552
And it's ignoble.

45
00:05:48,701 --> 00:06:17,004
meaning that it's not on the path and it's completely useless so that's his phrase you see remember it's painful, ignoble and unbeneficial there's absolutely no reason to do it so I think we can stretch this or at least I prefer to do this to stretch it to all this business around self-hatred around repression around that area where we're constantly judging ourselves

46
00:06:17,608 --> 00:06:45,252
putting ourselves down so it's not just a physical thing it's a mental thing and when we do that of course when we really suppress stuff that we don't want to to go near we know it leaks out in other ways in other sorts of neurotic patterns of behavior and stuff like that and if it's more of a conscious thing this constant self-judgment and doing ourselves down you know you're no good you're useless nobody loves you and all that sort of stuff

47
00:06:46,312 --> 00:07:15,814
it leads to depression doesn't it leads to despair so it's absolutely a waste of time to do that and when we see the danger of that sort of self-hatred that's when the meditation works for us because we turn round upon it we name it right we actually acknowledge what we're actually doing to ourselves that's the point right and in so doing we're pulling ourselves out of it we're finding another position right

48
00:07:16,115 --> 00:07:25,365
And remember that it's never getting into the head of it, never getting into the talk of it, or the speech of it, or trying to argue with it, or trying to make it see another point.

49
00:07:25,446 --> 00:07:45,649
It's always about sinking into the heart and feeling the self-hatred that we have towards ourselves, the self-judgment, and just being there with it, the unforgiving nature that we have sometimes towards ourselves, our unkindness towards ourselves, and just to stay with that and wait for it to pass, and to recognize it as just another mental state.

50
00:07:45,865 --> 00:07:47,086
not me, not mine.

51
00:07:47,365 --> 00:07:48,266
That's the important thing.

52
00:07:48,908 --> 00:07:54,312
See, every time, remember, we identify with this stuff, it's actually harming us.

53
00:07:54,333 --> 00:07:57,497
We're actually telling this very state of mind to do us harm.

54
00:07:58,617 --> 00:08:02,240
Every time we have these thoughts like, you know, you're useless and no good.

55
00:08:02,841 --> 00:08:03,543
I am useless.

56
00:08:03,882 --> 00:08:06,024
See, the I, how do you get out of that?

57
00:08:06,826 --> 00:08:07,927
There's no escape from that.

58
00:08:09,427 --> 00:08:09,928
You're in it.

59
00:08:10,189 --> 00:08:14,033
You are the one who is useless, who is horrible.

60
00:08:14,317 --> 00:08:17,161
whom nobody can possibly love and all that sort of stuff.

61
00:08:17,620 --> 00:08:22,608
So remember that that's also mortifying ourselves, you see.

62
00:08:23,189 --> 00:08:29,958
And that's often can be confused with humility in its more subtle sense.

63
00:08:30,538 --> 00:08:41,033
We think that we're being humble by doing ourselves down, by always undermining our self-esteem.

64
00:08:41,705 --> 00:09:10,176
sometimes we can mistake that for a sense of humility this is the way I really am but in fact it's just another form of self-hatred now one of the interesting things about these two types the type that is self-indulgent and the type that is very self-hating is that it comes out in the way that we look at rules and regulations

65
00:09:10,982 --> 00:09:14,967
So those people who tend to be self-indulgent are very easy with rules.

66
00:09:15,288 --> 00:09:18,712
And if anything, they become lax.

67
00:09:18,732 --> 00:09:19,553
It moves that way.

68
00:09:20,355 --> 00:09:29,967
Whereas people who are very self-hatred, who have this problem with an aversion, an averse type personality, get very tight around rules.

69
00:09:30,107 --> 00:09:30,828
It's like a prison.

70
00:09:32,090 --> 00:09:37,798
And they can't distinguish, for instance, the moral law from rules and regulations of society.

71
00:09:38,899 --> 00:09:40,280
It's very difficult for them to

72
00:09:40,615 --> 00:09:41,655
to make that distinction.

73
00:09:41,676 --> 00:09:43,918
It's all to do with rules and regulations.

74
00:09:46,241 --> 00:09:54,130
I remember Douglas Bader, you know, the war hero, the guy who flew all the planes and then crashed and smashed his legs up and started up the homes, didn't he?

75
00:09:54,851 --> 00:09:56,333
Douglas Bader Holmes, wasn't he?

76
00:09:56,354 --> 00:09:57,115
Yeah.

77
00:09:57,134 --> 00:10:01,681
So I remember him saying something along the lines of that, because he constantly broke rules.

78
00:10:03,503 --> 00:10:10,250
He said something along the lines that rules are like chains to idiots or fools.

79
00:10:10,770 --> 00:10:40,744
but to the wise their guidelines and when we are if we tend to be the sort of person who is very tight around themselves always self-criticizing always criticizing themselves they use rules in order to protect themselves from their own criticism because every time they break a rule they get the guilt see they get the guilt about having done something and then again it reinforces the feeling of I'm horrible, I'm terrible

80
00:10:41,769 --> 00:11:05,753
so there's a lot of ramifications around this whole business of self-mortification now I've really stretched this because I don't think the Buddha himself was thinking about that when he wrote this I think he's in his own time in his own place he's really talked about these practices that were going on at his time now then he goes on to say

81
00:11:06,086 --> 00:11:19,769
that without veering towards either of these extremes, the Tathāgata has awakened to the middle way, which gives rise to vision, which gives rise to knowledge, and leads to peace, to direct knowledge, to enlightenment, to Nibbāna.

82
00:11:19,788 --> 00:11:24,557
So, one of the virtues that we have is renunciation.

83
00:11:25,217 --> 00:11:28,001
Now, renunciation isn't self-mortification.

84
00:11:28,062 --> 00:11:29,404
We're not trying to punish ourselves.

85
00:11:29,524 --> 00:11:32,769
What we're trying to do is trying to find out where the attachment is.

86
00:11:33,356 --> 00:11:40,105
So when you walk into the kitchen and you think, I'll have a biscuit, see?

87
00:11:40,686 --> 00:11:48,475
So if you just bring out the biscuit and hold it in front of you, you see, and just feel the attachment and then say, well, I won't have it now.

88
00:11:50,157 --> 00:11:52,500
And put it back in the tin, you see?

89
00:11:53,020 --> 00:11:56,504
Now that sort of renunciation would be the middle way.

90
00:11:57,025 --> 00:11:58,548
You're not doing it out of self-hatred.

91
00:11:58,727 --> 00:12:00,629
You're doing it to let go of attachment to biscuits.

92
00:12:01,268 --> 00:12:12,241
I mean, one of the things I put to people is just choose your best TV program and get your biscuit and your cup of tea and just sit there and just don't turn it on.

93
00:12:14,605 --> 00:12:21,833
And just be there knowing that the football match is on, knowing that the next episode, which is the crucial episode, is next.

94
00:12:22,394 --> 00:12:30,684
And it's just feeling that desire and letting it go, which is the whole thing about

95
00:12:31,019 --> 00:12:59,034
desire is the problem attachment is the problem and it's just letting go so that would be the middle way you see when it comes to this business of mortification you are in a sense not feeding into the appetite to the body you're doing outwardly what self-mortificators would seem to be doing but for a completely different reason you're not punishing the body you're not thinking that this is going to somehow

96
00:12:59,351 --> 00:13:22,322
get you a better rebirth or whatever or it might because you're letting go of attachment it's more in the sense of seeing that attachment is actually suffering and every time you feed into it it creates more suffering so by renouncing it and by feeling the pain of letting go right the pain of letting go that's a healing pain that lets that finally undermines this whole business of attachment

97
00:13:25,711 --> 00:13:29,394
So then he goes on after this to go on to the middle path.

98
00:13:29,433 --> 00:13:31,535
So that's another little homily.

99
00:13:33,857 --> 00:13:36,441
So that's his opening in statement, you see.

100
00:13:36,941 --> 00:13:39,663
That's the platform of his whole teaching.

101
00:13:39,703 --> 00:13:41,465
It begins by this statement.

102
00:13:42,086 --> 00:13:47,250
Monks, there are these two extremes which should not be followed by one who's gone forth into homelessness.

103
00:13:47,850 --> 00:13:48,370
What to?

104
00:13:48,751 --> 00:13:54,537
The pursuit of happiness in sensual pleasures, which is low, vulgar,

105
00:13:54,888 --> 00:14:06,320
the way of worldliness, ignoble and unbeneficial, and the pursuit of self-mortification, which is painful, ignoble and unbeneficial.

106
00:14:06,340 --> 00:14:22,076
Without veering towards either of these extremes, the Tathagata has awakened to the middle way, which gives rise to vision, which gives rise to knowledge, and leads to peace, peace, to direct knowledge, to enlightenment, to nirvana.

107
00:14:23,778 --> 00:14:26,528
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

108
00:14:27,934 --> 00:14:35,846
May you be liberated sooner rather than later.

